  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA180-kiḷavi">itu talaimakaṟku vāyiṉērnta tōḻi talaimakaḷiṭattup poṟāmai kaṇṭu colliyatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante, who had granted the door to HIM, said upon seeing jealousy on HER part.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA180">
<l>            paḻaṉap pākaṉ muyiṟumūcu kuṭampai</l>
<l>            kaḻaṉi nārai yuraittaliṟ cennel</l>
<l>            viravuveḷ ḷariciyiṟ ṟāa mūraṉ</l>
<l>            palarppeṟa ṉacaiyi ṉemmil vāralaṉē</l>
<l>            māyō ṇalattai nampi viṭalol lāḷē </l>
<l>            yaṉṉiyum periya ṉavaṉiṉum viḻumiya</l>
<l>            viruperu vēntar porukaḷat toḻitta</l>
<l>            puṉṉai viḻumam pōla</l>
<l>            veṉṉoṭu kaḻiyumiv viruvara tikalē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>The man from a village, where the eggs(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">mūcu</term> can be, according to the TL, a noun denoting an "unripe fruit". If we take the image of red and white serious, it clearly refers to the eggs in the nest here, and this is how the line is read by T.V.G. If, however, we want to stick to the meaning of the word to be found elsewhere in the NA (cf. NA 190.5 and 224.10), we will take it as a verbal root meaning "to swarm", i.e. "a nest swarming with red ants".</note> of the red ants</l>
<l rend="indent">by the jack tree near the tank, spread from the nest,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when the field heron grates(?)<note place="foot">T.V.G. names "to suck" as the meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">uraittal</term> here, once again unknown to the dictionaries, and in any case the heron here probably is not a heron.</note> [them], like red paddy mixed</l>
<l rend="indent4">with white grains,</l>
<l>he does not come to our house, which many yearn to obtain.</l>
<l>The dark one, trusting in [her? his?]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nalattai</term> might refer here either to HER beauty (and she trusts that it will bring him back in time), or to HIS good intentions.</note> integrity,</l>
<l>is not capable of letting go of [him].</l>
<l rend="indent">As the distress of the Puṉṉai tree</l>
<l rend="indent2">that had been destroyed on the battlefield of the great king,</l>
<l rend="indent3">who was superior to Periyaṉ himself, Aṉṉi,<note place="foot">I cannot really explain the syntax of line 6. Is <term xml:lang="ta">avaṉiṉum</term> here used as <term xml:lang="ta">tāṉiṉum</term>? And what of the -<term xml:lang="ta">um</term> going with <term xml:lang="ta">Aṉṉi</term>? The story itself seems to be about a long-wearing strife between two chieftains, with parallels in AN 45, 126, 145, 196, 262.</note></l>
<l>the hostility of these two will pass away with me.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
